html<!DOCTYPE html> #just tells the browser "this is an HTML file." Always the first line, never changes.
<html>
    <head># metadata about the page. Things the browser needs to know but the user doesn't
    #see, like the page title, links to CSS files, etc.

    </head>
    <body>#everything the user actually sees on the page lives here.

    </body>
</html>
----------------- above is the skeleton of all HTML structure--------------------------------
HTML is built from tags. Almost every tag has an opening and closing pair:
<h1>Welcome to GameTracker</h1> #<h1> opens it, </h1> closes it. Whatever is between them is
#affected by that tag.

<title> — sets the name shown on the browser tab
<h1> through <h6> — headings, largest to smallest
<p> — paragraph, normal body text
<form> — creates a form for user input
<input> — a text field for the user to type in
<button> — a clickable button

----------------------------current example------------------------------------------------
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>#The root tag. Everything in your page lives inside this.
    <head>
        <title>GameTracker</title>#sets what appears on the browser tab.
    </head>
    <body>#everything from down here is what the user actually sees on the page
        <h1>Welcome to GameTracker</h1>#biggest heading level
   <form method="POST">#Creates a form
   #a form is just a way for a user to send data to your server through the browser.
   #The method="POST" tells the browser to send the form data as a POST request when submitted
   #GET — fetching/retrieving data from the server. Just asking for something,
   #By default flask only accepts GET so you need to add POST to that list.
   #@app.route('/',methods = ["GET","POST"])
#POST — sending data to the server. Like submitting a form with a game title.
        <input type="text" name="game" placeholder="Enter a game">
        #A text field. Three things happening here:
        #type="text" — makes it a text input box
        #name="game" — this is how Flask identifies it.
        #[used in the python program] - new_game = request.form["game"]
        #placeholder="Enter a game" — the grey hint text inside the box before the user types anything
        <button type="submit">Add Game</button>#A button that submits the form when clicked.
        #type="submit" is what triggers the POST request.
    </form>

    {% for game in games %}#Jinja2 loop — iterates over the games list passed in from Python
    #and renders each one as a paragraph.
    #[used in python program] - games = ["Elden Ring","Halo","Fifa"]
        <p>{{ game }}</p>#take whatever value game holds right now and print it here.
    {% endfor %}#This closes the for loop.
    #{{ }} — for displaying values
    #{% %} — for logic like loops and conditionals
    </body>
</html>

